<h2>Chapter 3: Content Marketing and Blogging</h2>
<p>Content marketing is the engine behind organic search. Without content, there is nothing to rank. But quantity alone does not work. The approach matters.</p>
<h3>Publish at the Right Frequency</h3>
<p>Companies that publish <a href="https://www.hubspot.com/marketing-statistics">16+ blog posts per month</a> get 3.5x more traffic than those publishing 0 to 4. That is not a magic number. The principle is that consistent publishing builds a library of indexed pages. Each page is a new entry point from search.</p>
<p>Our <a href="/blog/blog-frequency-study/">blog frequency study</a> breaks down the exact publishing cadence by business size.</p>
<h3>Write for Search Intent</h3>
<p>Every piece of content should target a specific search query. Before writing, search the keyword on Google. Look at what ranks.</p>
<ul>
<li>If the top results are how-to guides, write a how-to guide.</li>
<li>If the top results are listicles, write a listicle.</li>
<li>If the top results are product comparisons, write a comparison.</li>
</ul>
<p>Matching format to intent is the single biggest factor in whether your content ranks. A 5,000-word guide will not rank for a query where Google shows quick answer boxes.</p>
<h3>Update Existing Content</h3>
<p>Old content decays. A blog post that ranked #3 two years ago might sit on page 4 today. Content refresh is one of the fastest ways to recover lost traffic.</p>
<p>Audit your top 20 pages by traffic. Check if the information is current. Add new data points. Update screenshots. Expand thin sections. Then update the published date.</p>
<p>Sites that refresh content quarterly see <a href="https://www.semrush.com/blog/content-refresh/">106% more organic traffic growth</a> than those that only publish new articles.</p>
<h3>Create Content That Earns Links</h3>
<p>Not all content attracts backlinks. Data studies, original research, free tools, and visual assets earn links naturally. A single data study can generate more backlinks than 50 standard blog posts.</p>
<p>Think about what other websites in your industry would want to reference. Industry benchmarks, survey results, and calculators are reliable link magnets.</p>
