<p>Facebook dominates referral traffic by a wide margin. But the platform where your audience already spends time matters more than aggregate data.</p>
<h3>Optimize for Clicks, Not Likes</h3>
<p>Most social content gets engagement but zero clicks. The fix: stop posting content that resolves entirely within the platform. Share a stat, a finding, or a question that requires clicking through to get the full answer.</p>
<p><strong>Formats that drive clicks:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Data snippets with "full breakdown in the link"</li>
<li>Carousel posts where the last slide links to the article</li>
<li>Thread starters on X that end with a link to the full guide</li>
<li>Short video clips with a CTA to read the detailed version</li>
</ul>
<h3>Use Social Proof to Amplify</h3>
<p>Posts that already have engagement get shown to more people. Before sharing a new article publicly, share it with your team, email list, or close network first. Ask for genuine reactions. That initial engagement signals the algorithm to push the post further.</p>
<p>For a deeper strategy on social media and search working together, our guide on <a href="/blog/does-social-media-help-seo/">does social media help SEO</a> covers the relationship between the two.</p>
<p>For contractors and service businesses specifically, our <a href="/blog/social-media-for-contractors/">social media for contractors guide</a> covers industry-specific tactics.</p>
<h2>Chapter 5: Email Marketing</h2>
<p>Email marketing generates <a href="https://www.litmus.com/resources/email-marketing-roi">$36 for every $1 spent</a>. It is the only traffic channel you fully own. Algorithms cannot reduce your reach. Platform changes cannot kill your distribution.</p>
<h3>Build the List Before You Need It</h3>
<p>Every page on your site should have an email capture mechanism. The most effective formats:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Exit-intent popups</strong> with a specific lead magnet (not "subscribe to our newsletter")</li>
<li><strong>Inline content upgrades</strong> (a downloadable version of the article the reader is already on)</li>
<li><strong>Free tools or calculators</strong> that require an email to save results</li>
<li><strong>Gated templates</strong> (checklists, spreadsheets, swipe files)</li>
</ul>
<p>A list of 1,000 engaged subscribers who open your emails drives more traffic than 50,000 social media followers who never see your posts.</p>
<h3>Send Traffic-Driving Emails</h3>
<p>Every email you send is a traffic opportunity. Do not just announce new blog posts. Give the reader a reason to click.</p>
<p><strong>High-click email formats:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>"We analyzed [X]. Here is what we found." (data tease)</li>
<li>"The [topic] mistake that costs you [specific amount]." (problem hook)</li>
<li>"[Number] things that changed about [topic] this month." (news roundup)</li>
<li>"Here is the exact [template/process] we use for [outcome]." (resource share)</li>
</ul>
<p>Send 1 to 2 emails per week. More frequent sends reduce open rates. Less frequent sends make subscribers forget who you are.</p>
