<h2>Chapter 6: Paid Advertising</h2>
<p>Paid channels now account for <a href="https://contentsquare.com/guides/digital-experience-benchmark/traffic/">nearly 42% of all website traffic</a>. That number grew 18% year-over-year in 2025. Paid traffic is not a shortcut. It is a legitimate channel that compounds when paired with organic efforts.</p>
<h3>Google Ads for High-Intent Traffic</h3>
<p>Google Ads captures people actively searching for what you offer. The conversion rates are higher than any other paid channel because intent is built into the query.</p>
<p><strong>Start with branded and competitor keywords.</strong> These have the highest conversion rates and lowest cost per click. Then expand to high-intent commercial keywords in your niche.</p>
<p>For a detailed comparison of when to use paid vs. organic, see our <a href="/blog/google-ads-vs-seo/">Google Ads vs SEO breakdown</a>.</p>
<h3>Retargeting for Return Visits</h3>
<p>97% of first-time visitors leave without converting. Retargeting ads bring them back. Set up retargeting pixels on your site and serve ads to people who visited specific pages but did not take action.</p>
<p>Retargeting typically costs 50 to 70% less per click than cold traffic campaigns. The audience already knows your brand.</p>
<h3>Paid Social for Awareness</h3>
<p>Paid social works differently than paid search. The audience is not searching. They are browsing. Use paid social to amplify your best organic content to a wider audience.</p>
<p>Boost your top-performing blog posts to lookalike audiences. If a post already gets organic engagement, paying to expand its reach is a high-probability bet.</p>
<p>Our <a href="/blog/seo-vs-ppc/">SEO vs PPC guide</a> covers how to allocate budget between the two channels.</p>
<h2>Chapter 7: Community, Forum, and Reddit Traffic</h2>
<p>Most traffic guides ignore this channel entirely. That is a mistake.</p>
<h3>Reddit as a Traffic Source</h3>
<p>Reddit receives <a href="https://www.demandsage.com/website-traffic-statistics/">933 million organic search visits per month</a>. Google is surfacing Reddit threads in search results more than ever. A well-received Reddit post can drive traffic directly and rank in Google for years.</p>
<p><strong>The rules for Reddit traffic:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Contribute value for 30 days before posting any links.</li>
<li>Follow the 90/10 rule: 90% helpful comments, 10% self-promotion.</li>
<li>Answer questions in detail within the thread. Then add "I wrote a full breakdown here: [link]" at the end.</li>
<li>Target subreddits with 10,000 to 500,000 members. Too small and there is no audience. Too large and your post gets buried.</li>
</ul>
<p>Reddit users are aggressive about detecting self-promotion. If your post reads like marketing, it will get downvoted and removed. Write like a person sharing something useful. Not like a brand pushing content.</p>
<h3>Niche Forums and Communities</h3>
<p>Industry-specific forums, Slack groups, Discord servers, and Facebook groups drive highly targeted traffic. The volume is lower than search or social. But the conversion rates are higher because the audience is already engaged with your topic.</p>
<p>Find 5 to 10 active communities in your niche. Become a regular contributor. Share insights, answer questions, and reference your content only when it genuinely answers someone's question.</p>
<h3>Quora and Q&amp;A Platforms</h3>
<p>Quora answers rank in Google. A detailed answer to a popular question can drive traffic for years. Focus on questions with high view counts and weak existing answers. Write 300 to 500 word answers. Include a link to your full article at the end.</p>
