<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>How can I get more website traffic for free?</strong></p>
<p>The highest-impact free methods are SEO, blogging, and community participation. Publish keyword-targeted blog posts consistently. Optimize every page for on-page SEO. Contribute to Reddit and niche forums where your audience already gathers. These methods cost time but zero dollars.</p>
<p><strong>How long does it take to increase website traffic?</strong></p>
<p>It depends on the channel. Paid ads drive traffic within days. Email marketing works within hours of sending. SEO and content marketing take 60 to 90 days for initial ranking movement and 6 to 12 months for compounding results. The businesses that succeed are the ones that stick with organic strategies past the 90-day mark.</p>
<p><strong>What is the fastest way to get website traffic?</strong></p>
<p>Paid advertising is the fastest method. Google Ads and paid social can drive targeted visitors within 24 hours of launching a campaign. For free methods, sharing content in active Reddit threads or email lists generates traffic within days.</p>
<p><strong>Does social media increase website traffic?</strong></p>
<p>Social media accounts for only 4% of total website traffic across all industries. Facebook drives 71.58% of all social referral traffic. Social works best as an amplification channel for content that already performs well organically. It should not be your primary traffic strategy.</p>
<p><strong>Why is my website traffic dropping?</strong></p>
<p>The most common causes: Google algorithm updates, increased zero-click searches (60% of queries end without a click), AI Overviews reducing organic CTR by 47%, content decay on older pages, and technical issues like slow page speed or broken links. Run a site audit, check Search Console for ranking drops, and refresh your top pages.</p>
<p><strong>How many blog posts do I need to get traffic?</strong></p>
<p>Businesses publishing 16+ posts per month get 3.5x more traffic than those publishing 0 to 4. But quality matters as much as quantity. 30 well-researched, keyword-targeted articles outperform 100 thin posts. Aim for at least 8 to 12 posts per month if you are serious about organic growth.</p>
